\section{$50 :50$ Beam splitter transformation for ${ | {n,n} \rangle}$ state}


As an initial state we take ${ | {n,n} \rangle}$ which is two-mode $2n$--photon Fock state. We can express this state in terms of creation operators formalism 
\begin{eqnarray}
{ | {n,n} \rangle} = \frac{1}{n!} (a^{\dagger} b^{\dagger})^n { | {\Omega} \rangle},
\end{eqnarray}
where $a^{\dagger}$ and $b^{\dagger}$ stand for creation operators for two spatial modes and ${ | {\Omega} \rangle}$ is a vacuum state.
Let us denote the $50:50$ beam splitter transformation by $\mathcal{U}_{BS}$. Hence we get
\begin{eqnarray}
{ | {\psi } \rangle} = \mathcal{U}_{BS}{ | {n,n} \rangle} =  \frac{1}{2^n} \frac{1}{n!} [(c^{\dagger}+d^{\dagger})(c^{\dagger}-d^{\dagger})]^n { | {\Omega} \rangle} \\ \nonumber
= \frac{1}{2^n} \frac{1}{n!} (c^{\dagger 2}-d^{\dagger 2})^n { | {\Omega} \rangle} \\ \nonumber
= \frac{1}{2^n} \frac{1}{n!} \sum^n_{k=0} {{n}\choose{k}} \hat{c}^{\dagger 2(n-k)} \hat{d}^{\dagger 2k} { | {\Omega} \rangle},
\end{eqnarray}
where $c^{\dagger}$ and $d^{\dagger}$ are creation operators for modes after beam splitter. Moreover the operators $c^{\dagger}+d^{\dagger}$ and $c^{\dagger}-d^{\dagger}$ commute. 
Using the action of an creation operator on vacuum state the state reads 
\begin{eqnarray}
{ | {\psi } \rangle} = \frac{1}{2^n} \frac{1}{n!} \sum^n_{k=0} {{n}\choose{k}} \sqrt{[2(n-k)]!} \sqrt{(2k)!} \\ \nonumber
\times{ | {2(n-k),2k} \rangle} \nonumber
\label{AfterBS}
\end{eqnarray}
Let us notice that there are only two components in the state (\ref{AfterBS}), which reveal no coincidences, namely for $k=0$ and $k=n$.

\section{$50 :50$ Beam splitter transformation for ${ | {BSV} \rangle}_{\alpha }$ state with distinguishable photons}

We consider the state (\ref{BSValfa})
\begin{eqnarray}
{ | {BSV} \rangle}_{\alpha } = \frac{1}{\cosh{K}} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n!} \tanh^{n}K a_{h}^{\dagger n} \\ \nonumber
\times(\cos{\alpha}b_{h}^{\dagger}+\sin{\alpha}b_{v}^{\dagger})^n { | {0,0,0,0} \rangle} \nonumber ,
\end{eqnarray}
where $h$ and $v$ are horizontal and vertical polarization respectively and $\alpha \in [0,\frac{\pi }{2}]$ is a parameter which introduces a kind of polarization distinguishability measure in the spatial mode $b$. Please notice that for $\alpha = 0$ we reproduce the two -- mode bright squeezed vacuum state. After beam splitter the states takes the following form 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{U}_{BS}{ | {BSV} \rangle}_{\alpha } = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}A_{n}(c^{\dagger}_{h}+d^{\dagger}_{h})^n \nonumber \\ \left(\cos{\alpha}(c^{\dagger}_{h}- d^{\dagger}_{h})+\sin{\alpha}(c^{\dagger}_{v}-d^{\dagger}_{v})\right)^n { | {0,0,0,0} \rangle},
\end{eqnarray}
where $A_{n} = \frac{\tanh^{n}K}{n!2^n\cosh{K}}$. Using the binomial expansion we get
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{U}_{BS}{ | {BSV} \rangle}_{\alpha } = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\sum_{l=0}^{n}\sum_{m=0}^{n-l}\sum_{p=0}^{l}B_{n}^{k,l,m,p} \nonumber \\ (\hat{c_h}^{\dagger})^{2n-k-l-m}(d_{h}^{\dagger})^{k}(c_{v}^{\dagger})^{l-p}(d_{v}^{\dagger})^{p}{ | {0,0,0,0} \rangle},
\end{eqnarray}
where the coefficients $B_{n}^{k,l,m,p}$ equals
\begin{eqnarray}
B_{n}^{k,l,m,p} = \frac{(-1)^{k+p}\tanh^{n}K\sin^l{\alpha}\cos^{n-l}{\alpha}}{n!2^n\cosh{K}} \\ \nonumber
\times\binom{n}{k}\binom{n}{l}\binom{n-l}{m}\binom{l}{p}. 
\end{eqnarray}
Acting on vacuum by the creation operators one obtains (\ref{BSVout})
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{U}_{BS}{ | {BSV} \rangle}_{\alpha } = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\sum_{l=0}^{n}\sum_{m=0}^{n-l}\sum_{p=0}^{l}B_{n}^{k,l,m,p} \\ \nonumber 
\times \sqrt{(2n-k-l-m)!(l-p)!k!p!} \\ \nonumber 
\times { | {n-k-l-m,l-p,k,p} \rangle} \nonumber .
\end{eqnarray}
\section{Calculation of the expressions $G_{Q}$ and $C_{Q}$}
We present all calculations concerning the expressions (\ref{G_Q}) and (\ref{G2})
\begin{eqnarray}
G_{Q}={ \langle {\psi } | }n_{a} n_{b}{ | {\psi } \rangle} \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}
\\
\begin{eqnarray}
C_{Q}={ \langle {\psi } | }\frac{n_{a} n_{b}}{(n_{a}+n_{b})^2}{ | {\psi } \rangle} \nonumber
\end{eqnarray} 
In order to calculate expectation values (\ref{G_Q}) and (\ref{G2}) we use the fact that $f(\hat{n}){ | {n} \rangle} = f(n){ | {n} \rangle}$, where $f$ is a certain function of a photon number operator.																												
To calculate expressions (\ref{G_Q}) and (\ref{G2}) for state (\ref{BSValfa}), we should take summation to infinity into account. However for numerical reasons we cut sums to the certain $N_{max}$ according to the following criterion
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{n = 0}^{N_{max}}\frac{\tanh^{2n}K}{\cosh^2{K}} \geqslant 0.99,
\end{eqnarray}
where $\tanh^{n}{K}/\cosh{K}$ is the contribution of the $n$ -- th component in the state (\ref{BSV}). Let us notice that the smaller $K$ we take the smaller $N_{max}$ we need. For instance, for $K=0.5$ $N_{max} = 2$ is reasonable. After rather technical calculation we get
\begin{eqnarray}
C_{Q} = \sum_{n, n^{'}=0}^{\infty}\sum_{k,k^{'}=0}^{n,n^{'}}\sum_{l,l^{'}=0}^{n,n^{'}}\sum_{m,m^{'}=0}^{n-l,n^{'}-l^{'}}\sum_{p,p^{'}=0}^{l,l^{'}} \\ \nonumber B_{n^{'}}^{k^{'},l^{'},m^{'},p^{'}}B_{n}^{k,l,m,p} \\ \nonumber \frac{(k + m + p) (2 n - k - m - p) }{4 n^{2}} \\ \nonumber \Delta (n,k,l,m,p,n^{'},k^{'},l^{'},m^{'},p^{'})\label{G222}
\end{eqnarray}
\begin{eqnarray}
C_{Q} = \sum_{\sigma , \sigma ^{'}} \xi (\sigma , \sigma ^{'})\frac{A}{B}, \label{G22}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\Delta $ is a product of four Kronecker deltas. Namely,
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta (n,k,l,m,p,n^{'},k^{'},l^{'},m^{'},p^{'}) = \delta (k + m, k^{'} + m^{'}) \\ \nonumber \delta (n - k + l - m, n^{'} - k^{'} + l^{'} - m^{'}) \\ \nonumber \delta (p, p^{'})\delta (n - l - p, n^{'} - l^{'} - p^{'}).
\end{eqnarray}
For compactness we introduced simplified shortcut notation, $A = (k + m + p)(2 n - k - m - p), B = 4 n^{2}$. $\sigma$ and $\sigma ^{'}$ are appropriate multi-indices, $\xi (\sigma , \sigma ^{'})$ contains the rest of expression (\ref{G22}). Calculating of the expectation value $G_{Q}$ we follow the same way. In our shortcut notation one obtains 
\begin{eqnarray}
G_{Q} = \sum_{\sigma , \sigma ^{'}}\xi (\sigma , \sigma ^{'})A
\end{eqnarray}
